  "runtimeMin": 103,
  "format": "Sean, Van Lathan, and Amanda Dobbins spend an hour on Ryan Coogler's original vampire movie 'Sinners': the Delta blues, the musical centerpiece, the morality of who turns, and the box-office math on an R-rated horror movie. Then Coogler joins Sean to talk cameras, format, and the 25-year copyright deal he cut with Warner Bros.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Sinners’",
      "note": "with Van Lathan and Amanda Dobbins",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Sinners",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Coogler's first original film: 1932 Clarksdale, Mississippi, where twin brothers (Michael B. Jordan in a dual role as Smoke and Stack) come home to open a juke joint the same night a centuries-old Irish vampire, Jack O'Connell, starts building his flock. Three acts: 40 minutes of Delta-blues world-building, a musical set piece that folds a century of Black and Irish music into one shot, then a survival siege, shot on IMAX 65mm and 5-perf System 65. Newcomer Miles Caton plays Preacher Boy, alongside Hailee Steinfeld, Delroy Lindo, and Wunmi Mosaku. The group reads it as a movie about temptation and who counts as a sinner; the post-credits scene is set in 1992."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Ryan Coogler on ‘Sinners’",
      "guest": "Ryan Coogler on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Sinners",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Coogler on making something all his own after five studio pictures, and racing to shoot it before his longtime collaborators' lives pulled them elsewhere. On the cameras: Nolan told him not to be scared of the format, and the difference between the sync-sound System 65 body (too heavy to handhold) and the louder high-speed one. On the musical centerpiece, the moment that could 'only happen in a movie,' and pairing the vampires' cosmic horror with something cosmically beautiful. His Irish first name is why the Irish-folk-and-Delta-blues connection was on his mind."
        },
        {
          "title": "Don't Look Now",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "The film Coogler watched for himself before shooting; he'd owned it for years and it was 'clawing at' him."
        },
        {
          "title": "One of Them Days",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "His pick for the last great thing he saw: Keke Palmer and SZA, written by Syreeta Singleton. He loved that it felt like 'Friday' but feminine, and how it celebrated the resourcefulness of Black women."
        },
        {
          "title": "Bring It On",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "The movie he and his producer-wife saw on their first date: Peyton Reed's cheerleading comedy, part of his case for the theatrical experience."
        }
      ]
    }
